## Review Summary

Reviewed: `review-src/handler.ts` and `review-src/validate.ts` (commit `f377c05` -- "add unvalidated handler with JSON.parse")

### Findings

**Finding 1: `JSON.parse` without error handling** -- Confirmed, Critical. The snippet at `review-src/handler.ts:7` has no try/catch. Any malformed input throws a synchronous `SyntaxError` that propagates into the framework's error path. In Express-style handlers this becomes an unhandled exception; in async contexts it surfaces as an unhandled rejection. Root cause: treating untrusted input as trusted. Users hitting the endpoint with a malformed payload can trigger 500s or process crashes depending on the host; a typed `{ ok, value } | { ok: false, error }` result would contain the failure at the boundary.

**Finding 2: Falsy check drops valid values** -- Confirmed, Important. `if (req.body)` rejects `""`, `0`, `false`, and `NaN`. For a JSON endpoint the empty-string case is the likeliest real trigger (clients POSTing with no body). Should be `if (req.body != null)` or `typeof req.body === 'string'` depending on intent. Silent `null` returns are especially harmful because they mimic a valid "no data" response.

**Finding 3: `JSON.parse` on pre-parsed object** -- Confirmed, Important. Express's `express.json()` and Fastify's default parser both hand the handler an already-parsed object. `JSON.parse(object)` coerces via `String(object)` to `"[object Object]"` and throws. Severity depends on deployment context: if the handler runs behind a JSON-parsing middleware (unverified), this is Critical because every request fails. Verify middleware configuration before acting. If the framework passes raw strings, this is latent only.

**Finding 4: `validate` disconnected** -- Confirmed, Important. Dead export is a dependency-graph smell, but more importantly it reveals intent: the author meant to gate parsing on validation. Even if wired in, `x != null` is too weak (it would still let `""` and non-string types through to `JSON.parse`). Rewiring alone will not fix Findings 1 and 3.

### Cross-Cutting Patterns

All four findings share a single root cause: the handler treats `req.body` as trusted, well-typed data and performs no boundary validation. Finding 2 (truthy check), Finding 3 (type confusion with pre-parsed bodies), and Finding 1 (no error containment) are three facets of the same missing contract -- "what type and shape is `data` when it enters `process`?" Finding 4 confirms this was noticed during authoring (a validator was written) but never wired up, so the code ships with the author's own mitigation disabled. The fix is structural, not local: define an input contract at the handler entry (type guard plus schema check), make `process` accept only validated input, and wrap any remaining parse in a Result type. Patching findings individually will leave the same category of bug reachable via adjacent inputs; patching the contract closes all four simultaneously. No TypeScript types on `req`, `data`, or `x` amplifies every finding by disabling the compiler's ability to catch these at build time.
